        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What does the P0420 code mean and can a cleaner fix it?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The P0420 diagnostic trouble code means 'Catalyst System Efficiency Below Threshold (Bank 1).' It indicates your downstream oxygen sensor is detecting that the catalytic converter is not reducing emissions efficiently enough. A catalytic converter cleaner may resolve this code if the inefficiency is caused by carbon buildup or light contamination. If the code returns after treatment, the converter likely has internal structural damage and needs replacement."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How often should I use a catalytic converter cleaner?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "For preventive maintenance, using a catalytic converter cleaner every 3,000 to 5,000 miles or once per oil change interval is a reasonable schedule. If you are trying to fix an active check engine light or emissions issue, follow the specific product instructions — most recommend one to three consecutive treatments before expecting results."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can I use catalytic converter cleaner before an emissions test?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes. Many drivers use catalytic converter cleaners one to two tanks of gas before their scheduled emissions test. Products like CRC Guaranteed to Pass are specifically marketed for this purpose. For best results, add the cleaner, drive at highway speeds for at least 30 minutes to bring the converter to full operating temperature, and complete the full tank before testing."
          }
